  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Kings 25:3",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 25:3",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The famine prevailed in the city — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "So that for a long time they ate their bread, as Ezekiel foretold they should do, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 4:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "by weight and with care, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "drunk their water by measure and with astonishment, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "perceiving the quantity of it lessening fast every day, and having no hope of a fresh supply. Thus they were punished for their gluttony and excess, their fulness of bread, and feeding themselves without fear. At length ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "there was no bread for the people of the land — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For the common people, who, upon the approach of the Babylonian army, had flocked from all parts of the country, to secure themselves and their families, but only for the great men. Now they eat their own children for want of food, as had been foretold by one prophet, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 5:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) and is bewailed by another, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Lamentations 4:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c. Jeremiah, in this extremity, earnestly persuaded the king to surrender, but his heart was hardened to his destruction.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
